{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Some of the biggest names in marketing have had to apologize after consumers objected to ads that hinged on race, rape and suicide.", "abstract": "Major advertisers, including Ford Motor, General Motors, Hyundai Motor, Reebok and PepsiCo, are forced to apologize to consumers who objected to offensive ads primarily on social media that hinged on subjects like race, rape and suicide; public outcry shows that attempts by companies to be edgy and be noticed often go too far.", "section_name": "Business Day", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Stuart", "role": "reported", "lastname": "ELLIOTT", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"firstname": "Tanzina", "role": "reported", "lastname": "VEGA", "rank": 2, "organization": ""}], "original": "By STUART ELLIOTT and TANZINA VEGA", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/11/business/media/trying-to-be-hip-and-edgy-ads-become-offensive.html", "lead_paragraph": "Some of the biggest names in marketing have had to apologize after consumers objected to ads that hinged on race, rape and suicide.", "headline": {"main": "Trying to Be Hip and Edgy, Ads Become Offensive", "print_headline": "Trying to Be Hip and Edgy, Ads Become Offensive"}, "_id": "5190d2bd40e9ec457e2a08dd", "word_count": "1172", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2013/05/11/business/Ads1/Ads1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2013/05/11/business/Ads1/Ads1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 376, "url": "images/2013/05/11/business/Ads1/Ads1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2013/05/11/business/Ads1/Ads1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "376"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2013/05/11/business/Ads1/Ads1-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2013/05/11/business/